I"<h1 id="advance-ruby-object-specific-classes">Advance Ruby: Object-Specific Classes</h1>

<p>In Ruby you can create a class tied to an specific object. With this mechanism you can include methods to an existing object.</p>

<p>Sample:</p>

<div class="language-ruby highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="n">a</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"Hello World!"</span>

<span class="k">class</span> <span class="o">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class="n">a</span>
  <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">to_s</span>
    <span class="s2">"The value is '</span><span class="si">#{</span><span class="nb">self</span><span class="si">}</span><span class="s2">'"</span>
  <span class="k">end</span>
<span class="k">end</span>

<span class="n">a</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="nf">to_s</span>  <span class="c1"># "The values is 'Hellow World!'"</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>The notation <em>class « obj</em> allows us to include new methods to the object <em>obj</em>.</p>

